A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The Navy Environmental Sustainability Development to Integration (NESDI) program develops and transitions mission-critical environmental technologies and processes
that reduce operational risk, support compliance environmental regulations, and preserves access to essential shore infrastructure essential to Fleet readiness. As the
Department of the Navy's environmental shoreside RDT&E program, NESDI ensures that Fleet and shore operations can meet environmental obligations under key
statutes such as the Clean Air Act, Clean Water Act, RCRA, and NEPA, without disrupting mission execution.

 Aligned with the strategic direction of the Chief of Naval Operations' Navigation Plan 2022, the 2022 National Defense Strategy, and SECNAVINST 5400.15D, NESDI
 supports Naval SYSCOMS maintain operational effectiveness under increasing environmental constraints. Program investments directly address technical challenges
 across ranges, maintenance facilities, and shore activities to reduce compliance costs, avoid mission delays, and address emerging risks, ensuring continued support
 across the shore enterprise.

 Environmental Enabling Capabilities-2 (EEC-2) MAXIMIZE TRAINING AND TESTING RANGE REQUIREMENTS WITHIN ENVIRONMENTAL CONSTRAINTS:
 Ensures continued access to and use of Navy land and sea ranges by mitigating operational constraints driven by environmental regulations. Investments areas include
 modeling, risk assessments, and best management practices to address challenges related to UXO, munitions constituents, wetlands, and range management, tailored
 to the unique needs of Navy training and testing environments.

 Environmental Enabling Capabilities-3 (EEC-3) PLATFORM MAINTENANCE AND REPAIR WITH MINIMAL ENVIRONMENTAL FOOTPRINT: Supports the
 environmentally responsible maintenance and repair of Navy and Marine Corps platforms, including ships, submarines, aircraft, and unmanned systems. Investment
 areas reduce the use of hazardous materials, waste, and discharges at maintenance facilities, airfields, and ports. Resulting technologies include alternative coatings,
 process substitutions, and waste minimization approaches that reduce lifecycle costs, lower compliance burdens, and enhance the long-term supportability of
 operational platforms.

 Environmental Enabling Capabilities-4 (EEC-4). SUPPORT SHORE READINESS WITHIN ENVIRONMENTAL CONSTRAINTS: Addresses regulatory compliance
 challenges that affect the operation and sustainment of Navy shore infrastructure, including airfields, ports, and maintenance facilities. Investment areas deliver cost-
 effective solutions to reduce discharges and improve waste stream management through cost-effective technologies and process improvements. These efforts enable
 shore activities to meet regulatory requirements, reduce infrastructure lifecycle costs, and maintain uninterrupted mission support across the Navy shore enterprise.



