(AAP) on 17 Jul 2023 following a successful PEO Command, Control, Communications, Computers, and Intelligence (PEO C4I) decision disposition review on 21
Jun 2023. An AAP provides CITC with the greatest flexibility to sustain current capability while delivering incremental enhancements based on existing and/or new
requirements. Decision Authority was shifted to Program Manager, Cybersecurity Program Office (PMW 130) as part of the AAP transition. PMW 130 will continue to
deliver and sustain CITC capabilities as an AAP.

 As an AAP, CITC employs a flexible acquisition strategy based on the Joint Capabilities Integration and Development System (JCIDS) Information Technology (IT) to
 incrementally deliver capability that can respond to rapidly evolving requirements, priorities, and technology. Requirements for each capability increment are derived
 from the Platform for Risk Evaluation and Engagement to Neutralize Threat (PREVENT) Information Systems Capability Development Document (IS-CDD) via Capability
 Drops (CDs) and approved by the CITC Requirements Governance Board (RGB). Prior to the AAP transition, Capability Drop-1 (CD-1) defined the criteria required
 to achieve Initial Operational Capability (IOC) through rapidly fielding existing Commercial-Off-The-Shelf (COTS) tools under MTA. CD-1 was successfully fielded

 enhanced case management capabilities and additional Integrated Tool Suite (ITS) data sources. Capability Drop-3 (CD-3), approved by the CITC RGB in Jul 2023,
 expanded upon previous CD's by delivering automated and manual network Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) data ingestion for entity resolution, approval
 for data source ingests defined by stakeholders, and approval to import/export User Activity Monitoring (UAM) data to external agencies with stakeholder approval. As an
 AAP, CITC will continue to deliver via CDs based on PREVENT IS-CDD.$$, $$$$, $$N/A
