$$, $$bdea31197721e2dd65c2975052902fe2dddafdd130bccea0b364feb0d57e29d6$$, $${"A": "3694a90f051ba5fc8fa833a26b3fb58eae6c692e109e897e7d3f547c4d9ccded", "D": "75be7f54e9324fb4d9180ebaf7d1f9a6697b39d7b4f3e81c00fc1e43b879e028", "E": "a7968a126d91d52db210d206eddd96b7821e73f89791535c31a2f08ec07cfb1d"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY27/Air Force/FY27 Air Force Research, Development, Test & Evaluation  Volume IV.pdf$$, 851, $$2026-05-07T23:10:23.471687+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0708610F$$, 2027, $$- LOGIT is a portfolio of programs enabling the DAF logistics enterprise including aircraft maintenance, base-level supply operations, and the authoritative source
for all DAF items for aircraft and vehicles. The DAF logistics enterprise is currently comprised of disparate, antiquated, stovepiped systems and processes leaving
logistics operations inefficient, costly, and vulnerable. The goal of this portfolio is to modernize the logistics IT enterprise for a more efficient, cost-effective, integrated,
standardized, and resilient suite of systems. These systems will also incorporate the latest in cybersecurity measures and meet the statutory IT compliance requirements
including Financial Improvement and Audit Readiness (FIAR). The DAF logistics enterprise is comprised of multiple overarching functional areas to include field-level
maintenance, end-to-end supply chain management, and DAF item cataloging and provisioning. The current programs within this PE include: Enhanced Technical
Information Management System (ETIMS), Foundational Logistics Information Technology Enterprise System (FLITES), Supply Capability Initiative (SCI), Integrated
Logistics System-Supply (ILS-S), Enterprise Logistics Management System (ELMS), and Field Maintenance (Field Mx).

 - ETIMS is the system of record for all Technical Orders (TOs) and fully integrates electronic TOs (eTOs) supporting enterprise-wide distribution and viewing along with
 print-on-demand services. This system supports over 178K users across 385 sites worldwide. ETIMS is set to subsume multiple systems and capabilities terminating
 duplicate capabilities and achieving statutory IT requirements and FIAR compliance. The development efforts for ETIMS were completed in FY2025.

 - FLITES provides the capability to manage comprehensive, accurate, reliable item master data (e.g., accurate identification and authorization of owners and users
 of items). FLITES provides item standardization and configuration management from a single authoritative source ensuring foundational logistics processes are
 executed in concert to support the A4 logistics baseline. It enables key integration and transformation capabilities including Item Unique Identification (IUID) association
 to business transactions; streamlined management of part attributes across supply, finance, engineering, technology, transportation, maintenance, and vendor
 communities; and provide translation capabilities between functional and technical business communities and systems.

 - SCI is focused on modernizing the business processes and fundamentally enhancing supply operations and provide total asset visibility across the supply chain.
 These improvements have been identified in the DAF Logistics Capabilities Transformation Plan targeting improvements to manual processes in requisitioning, order
 management, item cataloging, inventory management, asset management, financial management, and supply chain analytics. This supports the DAF achieving total
 asset visibility at the base retail level enabling intelligent, data-driven decision-making based on accurate supply chain information. This initiative will drive base-level

Operational Systems Development
 supply enhancements in support of financial tracking of general funds and audit readiness. The efforts in SCI identified requirements for development efforts within the
 supply enterprise which will be met through modernization and capability upgrades in ILS-S and ELMS.

 - ILS-S is the current DAF Retail Supply System for Classes 2 (organizational equipment such as gear and tools) & 9 (repair parts including engines and aircraft
 components) for Base Level Users. ILS-S is used to manage procurement, order management, inventory management, asset management and all financial business
 operations supporting all accounting functions for auditability.

 - ELMS is a DLA program and the established DoW Joint system for retail supply Class 7 (major end items including large scale equipment such as vehicles, missile
 systems, etc.) items for base level users. ELMS is used to manage procurement, order management, inventory management, asset management and all financial
 business operations supporting all accounting functions for auditability. ELMS is currently in use and will be upgraded to meet DAF requirements.

 - Field Maintenance (Field Mx) is the software system for conducting maintenance operations in the field providing functionalities including planning, scheduling and
 execution of aircraft maintenance and sortie production. These efforts entail developing a classified Maintenance Information System (MIS) for the Nuclear Command,
 Control, and Communications (NC3) enterprise. These efforts also support providing effective deterrence, and ensuring a full-spectrum capable, high-end focused force.
 The development efforts will improve the DAF field maintenance capabilities across the Mission Generation Network (MGN) and Repair Network (RN) functionalities.
 The modernization of MGN will address the cumulative effort required to launch, recover, configure, inspect and repair aircraft. MGN and RN will standardize processes
 where appropriate, allowing for optimization of resources, enhanced visibility of assets, reduced rework, reduced variability, improved documentation and configuration
 management, all allowing for more rapid and informed decision-making at the base and enterprise level.

 - This program element may include necessary civilian pay expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such programs
 funds would be in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program element 0605827F, 0605828F, 0605829F, 0605831F, 0605832F, 0605833F, 0605898F,
 0606398F.

 - This requirement supports performance of a full financial audit as required by title 10 U.S.C. Chapter 9A, Sec 240-D.

 This program is in Budget Activity 7, Operational System Development because this budget activity includes development efforts to upgrade systems that have been
 fielded or have received approval for full rate production and anticipate production funding in the current or subsequent fiscal year.

