C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025      FY 2026       FY 2027
Title: Space-focused Basic Research                                                                                                    19.133       21.167        19.984
Description: Foster basic research discovery in physical and biological sciences that enhance U.S. Space Force's ability to
conduct global space operations. Current basic research efforts include, but are not limited to, Space Physics, Astrodynamics,
Space Biosciences, and Propulsion and Power.

FY 2026 Plans:

Research

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
- Seek to understand the solar terrestrial environment extending from the Sun through Earth's magnetosphere and radiation belts
to the mesosphere and lower thermosphere region to improve operational space weather forecasting.
- Advance the fundamental understanding of the physical processes that impact the motion and control of both natural and
artificial objects moving in the gravity fields associated with the Earth/Moon/Sun system needed to enable future operations
beyond geostationary earth orbits (X-GEO) operations.
- Conduct research in life sciences such as synthetic biology, biologically produced components, and biological processes to
understand and mitigate the impacts of harsh and remote environments on future operations and future assets.
- Explore theories, principles, and practical concepts of physical and biological sciences in harsh and remote environments to
identify solutions to current and future U.S. Space Force mission needs.
- Conduct foundational scientific research to enable greatly enhanced maneuver and power capabilities in the space environment.
- Explore novel ideas that may bridge these major efforts and enhance global space operations.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Continue to understand the solar terrestrial environment extending from the Sun through Earth's magnetosphere and radiation
belts to the mesosphere and lower thermosphere region to improve operational space weather forecasting.
- Continue to advance the fundamental understanding of the physical processes that impact the motion and control of both natural
and artificial objects moving in the gravity fields associated with the Earth/Moon/Sun system needed to enable future operations
beyond geostationary earth orbits (X-GEO) operations.
- Continue to conduct research in life sciences such as synthetic biology, biologically produced components, and biological
processes to understand and mitigate the impacts of harsh and remote environments on future operations and future assets.
- Continue to explore theories, principles, and practical concepts of physical and biological sciences in harsh and remote
environments to identify solutions to current and future U.S. Space Force mission needs.
- Continue to conduct foundational scientific research to enable greatly enhanced maneuver and power capabilities in the space
environment.
- Continue to explore novel ideas that may bridge these major efforts and enhance global space operations.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2027 decreased compared to FY 2026 by $1.183 million due to decreased emphasis on Space-focused basic research. This
reduction reflects programmatic adjustments to the DAF Science and Technology portfolio for strategic realignment to optimize
core research areas and improve resource efficiency. This will result in approximately 5 fewer grants awarded in Space-focused
basic research.
Title: Leveraging International S&T for DAF Advantage                                                                                 0.816       0.832          0.849
Description: Foster international basic research discovery by supporting direct interchanges with a broad range of key
international researchers and communities. Identify and leverage international scientific advances when appropriate.

Research

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025      FY 2026       FY 2027
FY 2026 Plans:
- Leverage international expertise to identify and maintain awareness of foreign scientific developments.
- Explore foreign investments and influence premier scientific leaders on specific topics of interest to the Department of the Air
Force.
- Pursue access to and enable transition of fundamental scientific discoveries relevant to the U.S. Space Force.
- Support international engagements by scientists and high-level DoW fundamental science delegations, providing primary
interface to coordinate international science and technology participation among DoW organizations.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Continue to leverage international expertise to identify and maintain awareness of foreign scientific developments.
- Continue to explore foreign investments and influence premier scientific leaders on specific topics of interest to the Department
of the Air Force.
- Continue to pursue access to and enable transition of fundamental scientific discoveries relevant to the U.S. Space Force.
- Continue to support international engagements by scientists and high-level DoW fundamental science delegations, providing
primary interface to coordinate international science and technology participation among DoW organizations.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2027 increased compared to FY 2026 by $0.017 million due to minor programmatic adjustments to the DAF Science and
Technology portfolio.
